<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-270-303  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 270 303.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  Dec 1989 v29 n12 p48(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Foreign language instruction and educational technology:possibilities and responsibilities for the instructor.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Regar, Ralph C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Recent products in computer-aided instruction and computer-aidedlanguage learning are effective tools.andP;  Foreign language teachershave an individual responsibility to understand this newtechnology.andP;  This involves understanding of software, hardware,and available training.andP;  Software can be prepared by the user,modified by the user, or purchased as a complete package.andO;Evaluative criteria are the same regardless of how it is produced.andO;Among sources of information for acquiring and evaluating hardwareand software are publications and district specialists.andP;  Cost,effectiveness, product design and specific features, andcompatibility with existing equipment or software should beconsidered.andP;  Among training sources are user groups, in-servicetraining, college courses, and professional journals.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EducationComputer-Assisted InstructionForeign LanguagesTutorialHardware SelectionSoftware SelectionApplicationsCost Benefit Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>